{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WvPA4frh4LEtwXJogG5BXv","type":"tool_result","content":"23-\n24-**Functional Requirements:**\n25:[Omitted long matching line]\n26-\n27-**Non-Functional Requirements:**\n--\n32-- Primary domain: Node.js CLI extending existing Commander.js architecture\n33-- Complexity level: Medium — one new architectural layer (drivers) on proven foundation\n34:- Estimated architectural components: ~8 new (3 drivers, 1 driver factory, 1 output contract module, 1 TUI workflow component, workflow schema extension, model resolver)\n35-\n36-### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n--\n48-1. **Driver lifecycle management** — Spawning, monitoring, timeout, termination, crash recovery applies to all drivers. Must be uniform regardless of whether the driver is in-process (Agent SDK) or CLI-wrapped (Codex, OpenCode).\n49-2. **Stream event normalization** — Every driver must produce `StreamEvent` objects. The TUI, cost tracker, and workflow engine all consume these. A driver that drops events or misparses output breaks everything downstream.\n50:3. **Output contract integrity** — Cross-framework task execution depends on output contracts being complete, correctly serialized, and crash-safe. A corrupted contract means the next task gets garbage context.\n51-4. **Model resolution cascade** — Task model → agent model → driver default must be consistent across workflow parsing, driver dispatch, and TUI display. A disagreement means the TUI shows one model while the driver uses another.\n52-\n--\n85-src/lib/\n86-├── model-resolver.ts   # New — task → agent → driver default cascade\n87:├── output-contract.ts  # New — serialize/deserialize cross-framework contracts\n88-└── ink-workflow.tsx     # New — TUI workflow graph component\n89-```\n--\n133-**Rationale:** No PTY avoids terminal emulation complexity. JSON output mode gives structured data. Line-by-line parsing is simple, streamable, and testable with fixture files.\n134-\n135:### Decision 3: Output Contract Format\n136-\n137-**Decision:** JSON files in `.codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json`. Written atomically (write to `.tmp`, rename). Read by next task's prompt injection.\n--\n157-```\n158-\n159:**Injection:** Workflow engine reads contract, appends structured summary to next task's prompt as context.\n160-\n161-**Rationale:** JSON is universal across drivers. Atomic writes (NFR15) prevent corruption on crash. Version field allows format evolution. Contracts are debuggable — plain files on disk.\n--\n218-2. StreamEvent production from different CLI outputs\n219-3. Error classification from framework-specific errors\n220:4. Output contract population from different agent outputs\n221-5. Health check implementation per driver\n222-\n--\n283-**Driver MUST NOT invent new categories.**\n284-\n285:### Output Contract Population Pattern\n286-\n287:**After each task dispatch, the workflow engine populates an output contract. Drivers MUST:**\n288-\n289-- Set `changedFiles` from file modification events (tool-complete for Write/Edit tools)\n--\n343-│   └── opencode.ts           # NEW — OpenCode CLI wrapper driver\n344-├── model-resolver.ts         # NEW — task → agent → driver default cascade\n345:├── output-contract.ts        # NEW — serialize/deserialize, atomic write, prompt injection\n346-└── stream-parser.ts          # EXISTING — shared line parsing utilities\n347-\n348-src/lib/\n349-├── workflow-parser.ts        # MODIFY — add driver/model/plugins to task schema validation\n350:├── workflow-engine.ts        # MODIFY — use driver factory, output contracts between tasks\n351-├── agent-dispatch.ts         # MODIFY — delegate to driver.dispatch() instead of direct SDK\n352-├── ink-workflow.tsx           # NEW — WorkflowGraph component\n--\n357-src/schemas/\n358-├── workflow.schema.json       # MODIFY — add driver, model, plugins to task definition\n359:└── output-contract.schema.json # NEW — JSON Schema for output contract format\n360-\n361-test/\n--\n367-│   │   ├── factory.test.ts\n368-│   │   └── model-resolver.test.ts\n369:│   ├── output-contract.test.ts\n370-│   └── ink-workflow.test.tsx\n371-└── fixtures/\n--\n381-\n382-.codeharness/\n383:└── contracts/                 # Runtime — output contract JSON files per task/story\n384-```\n385-\n--\n393-**Workflow Engine Boundary:**\n394-- Engine resolves drivers from factory, resolves models, dispatches tasks\n395:- Engine writes/reads output contracts between tasks\n396-- Engine does NOT parse CLI output or know driver internals\n397-\n--\n401-- `WorkflowGraph` component receives flow structure and task states as props\n402-\n403:**Output Contract Boundary:**\n404-- Contracts are JSON files on disk — written by engine, read by engine\n405-- Contracts are framework-agnostic — same schema regardless of source driver\n--\n413-| Stream Normalization (FR7-FR10) | Each driver's `parseLine()`, `stream-parser.ts` |\n414-| Workflow Config (FR11-FR15) | `workflow-parser.ts`, `workflow.schema.json` |\n415:| Cross-Framework Execution (FR16-FR20) | `output-contract.ts`, `workflow-engine.ts` |\n416-| Plugin Integration (FR21-FR23) | Each driver's `dispatch()` (plugins → CLI flags) |\n417-| TUI Workflow Graph (FR24-FR30) | `ink-workflow.tsx`, `ink-app.tsx`, `ink-components.tsx` |\n--\n432-    ↓\n433-    ├→ ink-renderer.update(event) → TUI renders\n434:    ├→ workflow-engine collects events → output-contract.write()\n435:    └→ next task: output-contract.read() → inject into prompt\n436-```\n437-\n--\n442-**Decision Compatibility:** All 6 decisions are internally consistent. `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` from Decision 1 feeds both workflow engine (Decision 3) and TUI (Decision 5). Model resolution (Decision 4) feeds `DispatchOpts.model` from Decision 1. Plugin pass-through (Decision 6) extends `DispatchOpts.plugins`. No contradictions.\n443-\n444:**Pattern Consistency:** All drivers follow identical class structure, registration, event ordering, and error classification. Output contracts are framework-agnostic by design.\n445-\n446:**Structure Alignment:** Project structure maps cleanly to decisions — `drivers/` for Decisions 1-2, `output-contract.ts` for Decision 3, `model-resolver.ts` for Decision 4, `ink-workflow.tsx` for Decision 5.\n447-\n448-### Requirements Coverage ✓"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_019LUaUpkJKAsHhoTwURUxyL","session_id":"d2473842-56c4-49f2-ab43-68fabe9113bb","uuid":"7693666e-3d07-4472-9e50-3f79829d6781","timestamp":"2026-04-03T10:46:26.929Z"}
